    "summary": "\"The metaphysical\" is correct; \"object\" is wrong",
    "content": "**\"The metaphysical\"** is correct. **\"Metaphysical object\"** is wrong, for a precise reason:\n\nThe author's 形而上 includes not only object-like things (concepts, \"things\") but also associations, frameworks, values, and the morphisms between them. The formal definition makes this explicit: a 形而上 is an *association* (联想, i.e., a morphism in E) that happens to be a universal property in some subcategory. Morphisms are not objects. Calling 形而上 a \"metaphysical object\" would import exactly the substance-ontology that the author is working to dismantle -- it would suggest that every metaphysical construct is a *thing*, when the author's whole point is that metaphysical constructs are *structural positions* (universal properties in subcategories).\n\nThat said, \"the metaphysical\" as a substantive adjective can be awkward in some English sentence structures. When the author uses 形而上 as a count noun (e.g., \"一个形而上\" or \"不同的形而上\"), I would suggest **\"a metaphysical construct\"** or **\"metaphysical constructs\"** (plural). \"Construct\" is neutral between objects, relations, and frameworks -- it means \"something constructed,\" which is exactly what the author intends (形而上 is built upon 形/现象).\n\nSo:\n- Generic/mass noun: **\"the metaphysical\"** (\"all 形而上 are constructions upon phenomena\")\n- Count noun: **\"a metaphysical construct\"** / **\"metaphysical constructs\"**\n- Never: \"metaphysical object\"\n"
  }
